2. Narrative Lesson Plan: The Role of Questioning

To teach this standard effectively, the lesson will utilize the three categories of questioning identified by Dance and Kaplan (2018) in Chapter 5: clarifying/probing, guiding/challenging, and assessing.

Phase 1: Launching the Task (Clarifying and Probing)

The lesson begins with a story context asking how many 3/4-cup servings are in 2/3 of a cup of yogurt. Following the techniques in Chapter 5, Dance and Kaplan (2018) explain on page 102 in the section regarding Questions That Clarify and Probe Thinking that the teacher will use clarifying questions to help students visualize the context of the problem. Instead of rushing to the algorithm, the teacher will ask what is known about the amount of yogurt available and what a serving represents in the story. These probing questions allow the teacher to better understand student thinking and ensure students understand the task before solving it, as Dance and Kaplan (2018) describe on page 105 in Chapter 5 in the section regarding Clarification and Probing.

Phase 2: Exploration (Guiding, Challenging, and Extending)

As students work with visual models, such as area models or number lines, the teacher will move through the room. According to Dance and Kaplan (2018), on page 108 in the section regarding Questions That Guide, Challenge, and Extend in Chapter 5, if a student is stuck, the teacher should use guiding questions to determine how to get started or ask what a specific fraction means in the student's model.

For students who find the answer quickly, Dance and Kaplan (2018) suggest on page 110 in the section on Questions That Guide, Challenge, and Extend in Chapter 5 that the teacher will push student thinking to deeper levels by asking extending questions. For example, the teacher might ask if the strategy would still work if there were 1.5 cups of yogurt or ask the student to create a similar problem involving a rectangular strip of land.

Phase 3: Whole-Group Discussion (Assessing Understanding)

During the final share, the teacher acts as a facilitator. Dance and Kaplan (2018) note on page 112 in the Teacher Talk Moves section of Chapter 5 that the educator will ask if anyone has questions for the presenter about how they used the area model. To assess the whole class, the teacher might ask why the class ended up with a quotient smaller than 1 in this problem. This helps determine if students are thinking critically about their choice of tool or strategy, which Dance and Kaplan (2018) define on page 115 as a goal in the Questions That Assess section of Chapter 5.

By modeling these questions, the teacher encourages students to move away from the preconceived notion that being questioned means they are wrong, instead fostering a culture where, as Dance and Kaplan (2018) state on page 120 in the section on Building Students’ Willingness to Answer in Chapter 5, answering and asking questions makes their brains grow stronger.
